s in soil and yeast in tissue","Hyphae in both soil and tissue","Yeast cells in soil and hyphae in tissue","Arthroconidia in soil and spherules with endospores in tissue"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides immitis\u003C/em\u003E is a dimorphic fungi. The organism exists in two distinct forms depending on its environment, forming \u003Cstrong\u003Earthroconidia in soil and spherules with endospores in tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. In the environment, it exists as a mold that produces barrel-shaped arthroconidia. When these are inhaled and reach body temperature, they transform into spherules containing endospores in infected tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this morphological transformation is crucial as it relates directly to the pathogenesis of coccidioidomycosis. The arthroconidia in soil are infectious when inhaled, and the development of spherules in tissue is a key virulence factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coccidioides immitis exists as a mold in soil and as spherules containing endospores in infected tissue.","Inhalation of arthroconidia from soil is the primary route of infection for coccidioidomycosis.","The dimorphic nature of Coccidioides is a key virulence factor in its pathogenesis."],"references":["Hernandez H, Erives VH, Martinez LR. Coccidioidomycosis: Epidemiology, Fungal Pathogenesis, and Therapeutic Development. Curr Trop Med Rep. 2019 Sep 15;6(3):132-144. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8340492/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61109"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61109"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T12:04:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T12:05:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"ite